The HD 192699 Exoplanetary System


Overview

HD 192699 is a star with 1.38 times the mass of the Sun, and 4.41 times its radius. It is located 234.38 light years away from the solar system and is estimated to be 1.8 billion years old, as compared to the Sun which is roughly 4.6 billion years old.

HD 192699 is known to have 1 exoplanets in orbit around it.


Exoplanets in the HD 192699 system


HD 192699 b

HD 192699 b was discovered by the Lick Observatory observatory, in 2007-08, using the radial velocity method. Its semi-major axis is 1.06 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of HD 192699 b is 666.528 times the mass of Earth. The radius of HD 192699 b is 13.400 that of Earth. At more than 50 Earth masses, HD 192699 b is a gas giant, a planet whose mass is mostly made up of hydrogen and helium, like Jupiter and Saturn in our solar system.
